messageBody:
Nathan Sharfi scripsit:

> - "object" (noun) with an .Et, not .Utter

Et is certainly what I say too.

> - Longman's has [prel.jud] (!) for "prelude"

Standard RP pronunciation. Americans have either /prE/ or /prEI/, and
in some uses even /pri/. As usual in AmE, the /j/ after coronals (/t/,
/d/, /l/, /n/) is lost, though Southerners sometimes keep it: my wife,
who's from North Carolina, thinks I sound like a gangster when I say
/tuzdi/ instead of /tjuzdEI/.

> - "subsistence" with an [s], not [z]

I can't find any dictionary that records /z/ in this word. My usual
dictionaries for pronunciation, BTW, are:

http://m-w.com (American)
http://ahdictionary.com (American)
http://oxforddictionaries.com (both American and British available)
http://dictionary.infoplease.com (American: it's Random House '97)
http://collinsdictionary.com (both American and British available)
http://www.macmillandictionary.com (British)

The OED, though great for history, can't be safely used for pronunciation:
too many of its pronunciations are a hundred years old and more.

--
